    "\n",
    "These single qubit unitaries are then applied on the quantum computer on the state $\\rho$. One measures for each unitary $u^{(r)}$ $N_M$ bistrings $\\{s_m^{(r)}\\}$ and access an estimation of $X(u)$ via \n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "X_e(u^{(r)}) = \\frac{2^N}{N_M(N_M-1)}\n",
    "    \\sum_{m \\neq m'} (-2) ^{-D[s_m^{(r)},s^{(r)}_{m'}]}\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "We obtain the purity of the state $\\rho$ based on the formula\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "[p_2]_\\mathrm{IS} = \\frac{ 1}{N_s}\n",
    "    \\sum_{r = 1}^{N_u} \\frac{n^{(r)} X_e(u^{(r)}) }{p_\\mathrm{IS}(u^{(r)})}\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    " where $N_s$ is the total number of unitaries $u$ collected by the metropolis algorithm which contains $N_u$ distinct ones and $n^{(r)}$ takes into account the occurence of each of unitary $u^{(r)}$ of the $N_u$ distinct samples and satisfies $N_s=\\sum_r n^{(r)}$.\n",
    " \n",
    " ### Example\n",
    " with $N=16$, $N_M=10\\times 2^{16}$, $N_u=100$, $p=0.25$, the script returns for three different simulated experiments\n",
